Importing data from spreadsheets is the primary way that you will bring data into R. We will look at the generalized case of â€œcomma-delimited filesâ€ (â€œ.csvâ€), then import files directly from Excelâ€™s proprietary format (â€œ.xlsxâ€). Finally, we will learn to import sequence files using a new, specialized package bioseq, that contains functions for importing and manipulating both nucleotide and amino acid sequences.

1 Comma-Delimited Files

The most common file type you will be importing into R is the comma-delimited file, or â€œcsvâ€ file. As I have previously explained, it is a basic text file that any text editor can read, but it contains its information in a structured way that allows the R function readr::read_csv() (VSS: package name followed by 2 colons followed by function name) to parse it into a meaningful R tibble.1

1.2 Arguments of the read_csv() Function

There are a few key arguments that you need to specify so the read_csv() function can find the data you want to upload to R and know how to parse it. However, I have not listed all the possible arguments here, just the most useful ones. First you need to give the data frame a name. You are going to assign a name to the tibble (â€œdfâ€ in the definition of read_csv() above) that you will refer to it by thereafter.

The first argument is the name of the file on your computer the function will be reading: file. The file name needs enough information about the path where the file is located to find it. This is a case where the here::here() function we have previously discussed comes in helpful since it defines a full path. In the example below, I will use here() to show you one of the ways I use to save me some pain.

â€œ.csvâ€ files have the option of putting the variable/column names in the first row. read_csv() assumes this is TRUE. If it is not, if the data does not include any variable names, then you need to set this argument to FALSE: col_names = FALSE.

The third argument, col_types =, is a bit more complicated. read_csv() will try to guess the correct data type for each column following Râ€™s rules for the hierarchy of data classes. Its guesses are generally quite good if the data is straightforward. However, if you want to specify the column types, you can put a string of characters in the place of NULL to represent the data types using the following letters:

  • c = character
  • i = integer
  • n = number
  • d = double
  • l = logical
  • f = factor
  • D = date
  • T = date time
  • t = time
  • ? = guess
    • to skip the column

Make sure that you have exactly the number of characters in your string as there are columns in the file. For example, if you have a data set with five columns, the first a string, the second a factor, the third a number, the fourth a column you want to skip and the last another character string, your column type argument should be col_types = "cfn-c".

The fourth argument gives you the chance to specify what characters define missing data (NA). read_csv assumes that either a blank string or the string â€œNAâ€ represents missing data. If you want to add others, you need to modify the string to include the value your data set uses. For example, some social science data sets use â€œ99â€ as an indicator of missing data. This doesnâ€™t work for hard science and it is pretty bad practice in social science as well. However, if you data set includes this option, you will want to specify the na = argument with na = na = c("", "NA", "99").

The final option covered here is defining how many rows of data you want to skip, not bring into your R tibble. Some data sets include at the top lines with metadata, information about how, when and where the data was collected. To skip these lines, you define a positive value for skip =. If there are three lines of metadata, then you will want to include the argument skip = 4. If the data set simply has a line with variable names and then rows of data, you can omit this argument entirely.

1.3 Example 1 - Simple Data Set

Here is a simple â€œ.csvâ€ file, classe_simples.csv that records the names, home state, age and scores on a standardized test (1 - 10).

To bring this file into R, we apply the function read_csv() explained above. First, we give the R object we will create a name, and then provide values for the arguments if they are needed. If we are using the default value shown above and in the help screen for this command, then we can omit the argument as R will use the default value.2 For this data, we create the data frame classe1 with the following command:

classe1 <- read_csv(here::here("classe_simples.csv"))
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   nome = col_character(),
##   estado = col_character(),
##   idade = col_double(),
##   nota = col_double()
## )
classe1
## # A tibble: 10 x 4
##    nome    estado idade  nota
##    <chr>   <chr>  <dbl> <dbl>
##  1 Pedro   DF        34  4.12
##  2 Joana   PE        59  6.1 
##  3 Isabel  SP        26  9.34
##  4 Pedro   GO        67  6.75
##  5 Bia     RJ        53  5.85
##  6 Pedro   RJ        51  7.49
##  7 Tomas   TO        46  5.78
##  8 Isabel  PE        66  4.2 
##  9 Tomas   GO        21  8.78
## 10 Ricardo TO        51  8.58

We can see that read_csv() produced a tibble with the same values as the original .csv file. Because the first line contained the variable names, we could omit the col_names = argument. We relied on the ability of R to parse the values of the four variables correctly. We can check in the report of the tibble above that it did parse them correctly. If we had wanted to put the col_types = argument manually, it would have been col_types = "ccnn".

1.4 Example 2 â€“ More Complex Data Set

Returning to the Albert Einstein Hospital sorological tests for COVID-19 antibodies, we will now import a 99 case version of the data, einstein_soro_tests.csv. This is the spreadsheet.

In this case, we can see the data will need some massaging to make it ready for analysis. The variable names are in the first line, so we can omit the col_names = argument. The patient idâ€™s (pacid), while clunky with so many characters, are clearly permissible character strings. The collection date of the sample (dt_collect) is a Date field, but given its non-standard format3, R will probably parse it as a character string. We will be able to reformat it as a Date variable in our subsequent tidying phase. The analysis field is clearly a text string. The result field should be numeric, but the text entries in the field (see line 5) force R to coerce the field to a character variable. The following two fields are all character strings, although the reference field could be transformed into a numeric value if we want to compare it to the result field.

The sex field is clearly a character string. However, it has only two values, so I would like to store it as a factor â€“ a categorical variable. To do this, instead of a â€œcâ€ for character variable, I will put an â€œfâ€ for a factor variable

The birth year (birth_yr) field will be imported as a numeric field. However, a careful look through the spreadsheet shows that there are three values of NA, so we will need to make sure that the na argument includes this value as an option. Finally, the state (uf) and city fields are character strings. Given this field-by-field analysis, we could use a col_types = argument of `col_types = â€œccccccfnccâ€.

We can deal with the text problem in the result field at the import step of our process by using the na = argument to specify â€œNÃ£o reagenteâ€ and â€œNULLâ€ as NA values. We can structure this argument by creating a vector with these two values and giving the na argument this vector: `na = c(â€œNÃ£o reagenteâ€, â€œNULLâ€, â€œNAâ€).

With this information, we can import the data.

einstein_soro <- read_csv(here::here("einstein_soro_tests.csv"), col_types = "ccccccfncc", na = c("NÃ£o reagente", "NULL", "NA"))
glimpse(einstein_soro)

2 Excel Spreadsheets (.xlsx)

Spreadsheets in Excelâ€™s proprietary format can be imported directly into R without having to save them as .csv files first. We use the readxlpackage. Its principal function is read_excel(), which permits you to work with either the older â€œ.xlsâ€ format or the current â€œ.xlsxâ€ format. Its overall structure is similar to that of read_csv(), with differences primarily related to the way it refers to column types for parsing. It also contains arguments so you can choose an individual sheet in a multi-sheet workbook or a specific region on a spreadsheet.

2.1 Arguments for read_excel()

As with read_csv(), we first give read_excel() the full path as the first argument. We can specify a sheet name (exactly as given in the Excel tab for that sheet in quotation marks) and then an Excel range, using the normal Excel cell reference notation (e.g., â€œA1:B25â€) with a colon separating two beginning and end of the range. The col_names = argument functions the same as with read_csv(). The col_types = has the same concept as the read_csv() equivalent, but a different notation. As before, you will need a vector of column types that has the same length as the number of columns. If you put only one type in the argument, R will use that type for all the variables. If you omit this argument, R will guess the best type of column type to give the data in the coludatemn.

VSS: Stick with giving a complete list or none. When you look back on your list, you want to be clear about what you did and why. Partial lists, relying on Râ€™s ability to recycle (i.e., repeat) column types can create some chaos.

The na = and skip = arguments function in the same way as their read_csv() equivalents.

2.2 Column Types in read_excel()

Column types here use whole words rather than single letters as in read_csv(). They include a simpler set than previously, but include all the major types we have covered so far. If you want to make a variable into a factor, for example, you will need to do it during your tidying phase as the option is not directly available here. Column types must be entered as a vector using c(). The column types availabe are

  • date
  • guess (trust R to make a good choice)
  • list
  • logical
  • numeric
  • skip
  • text

2.3 Spreadsheet Example

As an example, we will read in one of the new standard R data sets that deals with size measurements for penguins near the Palmer Research Station in Antartica. It describes eight characteristics of 344 penguins and is in the file penguins.xlsx. The file only has one sheet and we will use the entire sheet.

As you can see in the spreadsheet itself, some of the values are NA. Thus, to make sure that all the numeric values of variables such as bill_length_mm are stored in numeric form, we will need to specify a value for the na = argument of NA. If we do not, R will parse all the variables as â€œtextâ€ in readxlâ€™s parlance, that is, character strings. We can correct such an error easily in the tidying phase of our work, but we can do it more efficiently here. You will note that the behavior of the na argument is slightly different here than in read_csv. Here, the argument has no default terms for missing data. In read_csv, the default assumes that both NA and a blank space indicate missingness.

If we want to specify the column types, the vector c("text", "text", "numeric", "numeric", "numeric", "numeric", "text", "numeric) will correctly identify the types. However, Râ€™s parser will achieve the same result, so the argument is unnecessary.

penguin <- readxl::read_excel(here::here("penguins.xlsx"), na = "NA")
glimpse(penguin)
## Rows: 344
## Columns: 8
## $ species           <chr> "Adelie", "Adelie", "Adelie", "Adelie", "Adelie",...
## $ island            <chr> "Torgersen", "Torgersen", "Torgersen", "Torgersen...
## $ bill_length_mm    <dbl> 39.1, 39.5, 40.3, NA, 36.7, 39.3, 38.9, 39.2, 34....
## $ bill_depth_mm     <dbl> 18.7, 17.4, 18.0, NA, 19.3, 20.6, 17.8, 19.6, 18....
## $ flipper_length_mm <dbl> 181, 186, 195, NA, 193, 190, 181, 195, 193, 190, ...

3 FASTA Files

[If you are not a biology or medical student or you are not interested in genomic sequences, you may skip this section.]

FASTA is the most common way to store nucleotide (DNA or RNA) and amino acid sequences in bioinformatic applications. It is a text-based representation of the sequences using the standard single-letter codes. Each sequence can be preceded by a sequence name and comments. A file of FASTA sequences is again, like a â€œ.csvâ€ file, a simple text file that can be read by any text editor. However, to bring FASTA formatted sequences into R for processing and analysis, we use specialized packages and functions that understand the alphabet of sequences and can separate the sequence itself from its name and comment line.

There are a number of packages that have a FASTA reading and parsing function. A new package, bioseq is available on CRAN and its basic reading and analysis functions remove many of the eccentricities and difficulties that other packages and functions present.

VSS: bioseq is so new that it was not in the original set of packages to be downloaded in Chapter 1. So, before you try to use this command, you need to execute the following command in the Console: install.packages("bioseq").

The read_fasta() command only takes two arguments, the file (and its path) and the type of sequence you are loading. The default for the function is DNA, but you can specify â€œRNAâ€ or â€œAAâ€, in either of these cases.

The sequence we will import is the DNA sequence of the gag polyprotein of the HIV virus. We will be using one of the reference genomes of HIV, the HXB-2 genome. The sequence is stored in the file â€œHIVHXB.faâ€. This sequence is 1,503 base pairs long. In a text editor, it looks like this.

To import the file, simply execute the read_fasta() function with the file and sequence type.

seq <- bioseq::read_fasta(here::here("HIVHXB.fa"), "DNA")
stringr::str_sub(seq, 1, 80)
## [1] "ATGGGTGCGAGAGCGTCAGTATTAAGCGGGGGAGAATTAGATCGATGGGAAAAAATTCGGTTAAGGCCAGGGGGAAAGAA"

bioseq has created a vector, seq of the type we requested in the command. The following line shows the first 80 nucleotides of the sequence using the Tidyverse string manipulation package stringr. We will do much more with sequences and bioseq later in this text.
